<chapter xml:id="ch-chapter-2-quantifiers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Quantifiers</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      If we read the sentences, <q>He is taller than that,</q> or <q>She is from Darien, CT,</q> or even <q><m>x^2 \geq y + 4</m>,</q>
      we note that they are not statements because their truth values are ambiguous. After all, who is he? What is that? Who is she?
      Which values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are we considering? If we knew the answers to these questions, these sentences would be statements; 
      such sentences are called <term>propositional functions</term>, and we make statements out of them using quantifiers. 
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-propositional-functions">
    <title>Propositional Functions</title>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-propfunc">
      <notation>
        <usage><m>p(x)</m></usage>
        <description>simple propositional function</description>
      </notation>
      <notation>
        <usage><m>P(x,y)</m></usage>
        <description>compound propositional function</description>
      </notation>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>propositional function</term> is a sentence that becomes a statement when ambiguity is removed.
          We denote a propositional function as <m>p(x)</m> if it results in a simple statement or <m>P(x,y)</m> if it results in a compound statement. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-universal-quantifier">
      <notation>
        <usage><m>\forall</m>></usage>
        <description>universal quantifier</description>
      </notation>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a domain of discourse <m>D</m>, a <term>universal quantifier</term> is the specification,
          <q>for all <m>x</m> in <m>D</m>,</q> or, <q>for each <m>x</m> in <m>D</m>.</q>
          It is denoted <m>\forall x \in D</m>.
          The logical shorthand for a universally quantified statement is <m>\forall x \in D, p(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The statement, <q>For all real numbers <m>x</m>, <m>x^2 \geq 0</m></q> is a universally quantified statement with a truth value of true. 
          The statement, <q>For all real numbers <m>x</m>, <m>\tan(x)</m> is a real number</q> is a universally quantified statement with a truth value of false.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="def-existential-quantifier">
      <notation>
        <usage><m>\exists</m></usage>
        <description>existential quantifier</description>
      </notation>
      <notation>
        <usage><m>\backepsilon</m></usage>
        <description>such that</description>
      </notation>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a domain of discourse <m>D</m>, an <term>existential quantifier</term> is the specification, 
          <q>there exists <m>x</m> in <m>D</m>,</q> or, <q>for some <m>x</m> in <m>D</m>.</q>
          It is denoted <m>\exists x \in D</m>. An <term>existentially quantified statement</term> takes the form, 
          <q>there exists <m>x</m> in <m>D</m> such that <m>p(x)</m></q> or <q><m>p(x)</m> for some <m>x</m> in <m>D</m>.</q>
          The logical shorthand for an existentially quantified statement is <m>\exists x \in D \backepsilon p(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The statement, <q>There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 \geq 10</m></q> is an existentially quantified statement with a truth value of true. 
          The statement, <q>There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>\cos(x) > 2</m></q> is an existentially quantified statement with a truth value of false.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        Are the following quantified statements true or false? Justify your answers.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <statement correct="no">
              <p>
                <q>For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, <m>x^2 \geq y+4</m>.</q>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                This statement is false because there are pairs of real numbers like <m>x = 0</m> and <m>y = 1</m>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </li>
          <li>
            <statement correct="yes">
              <p>
                <q>There exist real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> such that <m>x^2 \geq y+4</m>.</q>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                This is true. The real numbers <m>x = 0</m> and <m>y = -5</m> satisfy the statement.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </li>
          <li>
            <statement correct="yes">
              <p>
                <q>For all real numbers <m>x</m>, there exists a real number <m>y</m> such that <m>x^2 \geq y+4</m>.</q>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                This is true. Given any real number <m>x</m>, taking any <m>y \leq x^2 - 4</m> satstifies the statement.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </li>
          <li>
            <statement correct="no">
              <p>
                <q>There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that for all real numbers <m>y</m>, <m>x^2 \geq y+4</m>.</q>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <response />
            <solution>
              <p>
                This is false. Given any candidate for <m>x</m>, we can take <m>y = x^2 -3</m> to build a counterexample.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-exercises">
    <title>Exercises</title>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        Let <m>P(x,y)</m> denote <m>x \geq y</m>.  Determine whether the following statement are true or false; justify your answer.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <statement correct="no">
            <p>
              <m>\forall x, y \in \mathbb{N}, P(x,y)</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </li>
        <li>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\forall x \in \mathbb{N}, \exists y \in \mathbb{N}</m> such that <m>P(x,y)</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </li>
        <li>
          <statement correct="no">
            <p>
              <m>\exists x \in  \mathbb{N}</m> such that <m>\forall y \in \mathbb{N}</m>,  <m>P(x,y)</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </li>
        <li>
          <statement correct="yes">
            <p>
                <m>\exists x,y \in  \mathbb{N}</m> such that <m>P(x,y)</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        Write down the negation of the following statements, moving the negation symbol <m>\lnot</m> as far to the right as possible. Use  symbolic logic notation.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\forall x \in A \left [ p(x) \implies q(x) \right ]</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\exists x \in A </m> such that <m> \left [ \left ( \lnot p(x)\right ) \land q(x) \right ]</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
             <m>\forall x \in A \left [ p(x) \implies \left ( \exists y \in B \text{ such that } \left [ q(x,y) \land r(x,y) \right] \right ) \right ]</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rewrite the following sentence using symbolic logic notation for the logical connectives and quantifiers 
         (<m>\mathcal{F}</m> denotes the set of all functions <m>\mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m>).
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>
            For any function <m>f \in \mathcal{F}</m> that is continuous on <m>[a, b]</m>, 
            there is some <m>c \in [a,b]</m>  such that for all <m>x\in [a,b]</m>, <m>f(c) \leq f(x)</m>.
          </q>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </section>

